WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:03.580
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.580 --> 00:00:06.990
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:06.990 --> 00:00:11.080
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:11.080 --> 00:00:15.980
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:15.980 --> 00:00:16.980
of videos.

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:19.340
Thanks for your help.

00:00:19.340 --> 00:00:24.000
Also, remember to download and use the Anki
flashcards with the link in the description,

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.890
which will help you very much in remembering
what you've learned.

00:00:26.890 --> 00:00:29.630
Let’s get started.

00:00:29.630 --> 00:00:35.800
In this video we’ll take a break from IP
addresses and take a look at switch interfaces.

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:40.999
When we configured IP addresses, I talked
about router interfaces a little bit.

00:00:40.999 --> 00:00:46.530
For example, we used the ‘show ip interface
brief’ command to check the Layer 1 and

00:00:46.530 --> 00:00:49.480
Layer 2 status of the interfaces.

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:53.440
I also talked about how router interfaces
are disabled with the ‘shutdown’ command

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:55.699
by default.

00:00:55.699 --> 00:00:59.579
This time we’ll take a look at switch interfaces
and see how they are different from router

00:00:59.579 --> 00:01:03.010
interfaces, and also how they are the same.

00:01:03.010 --> 00:01:07.969
Specifically, we’re going to talk about
configuring Layer 1 characteristics of these

00:01:07.969 --> 00:01:12.530
interfaces, such as speed and duplex.

00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:15.270
So let me introduce what we’ll cover in
this video.

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:19.640
I’ll talk about interface speed and duplex.

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:25.490
Speed refers to the data rate in bits per
second, such as 10, 100, or 1000 megabits

00:01:25.490 --> 00:01:28.000
per second.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.840
Duplex is something I mentioned briefly in
a previous video, basically it refers to whether

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:37.000
a device is able to both send AND receive
data at the same time.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.610
I’ll talk about speed and duplex autonegotiation,
which allows two devices to negotiate speed

00:01:43.610 --> 00:01:47.799
and duplex settings without us having to manually
configure them.

00:01:47.799 --> 00:01:50.090
I’ll talk about interface status.

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:55.369
I already talked about this in the previous
video on configuring router interfaces, but

00:01:55.369 --> 00:01:57.350
I’ll expand upon the topic.

00:01:57.350 --> 00:02:02.270
Finally, I’ll talk about interface counters
and errors.

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:06.659
Cisco devices keep various counters regarding
the traffic that passes through them, such

00:02:06.659 --> 00:02:08.920
as how many errors have occurred, etc.

00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:14.151
I’ll show you how to find and analyze these
statistics, and what kinds of errors there

00:02:14.151 --> 00:02:16.209
are.

00:02:16.209 --> 00:02:20.440
Also let me review one point about switches
that I mentioned in the very first video in

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:22.370
this series.

00:02:22.370 --> 00:02:31.020
Up top is a photo of a Cisco ASR 1000-X router,
and under it is a Cisco Catalyst 9200 switch.

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:34.569
What’s the big difference that stands out
here?

00:02:34.569 --> 00:02:37.150
How about the number of interfaces?

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:44.260
The router has 8 SFP interfaces for fiber-optic
cables, and then a few RJ45 interfaces for

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.739
the console port and such.

00:02:46.739 --> 00:02:54.330
The switch, on the other hand, has 4 SFP interfaces,
plus FORTY EIGHT RJ45 interfaces.

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:58.129
This is because switches are used to connect
end hosts to.

00:02:58.129 --> 00:03:04.689
This catalyst switch might have 48 PCs connected
to the RJ45 ports, and then connect to a router

00:03:04.689 --> 00:03:09.120
with the SFP fiber optic ports.

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:13.870
Next let me introduce the network topology
I’ll use for this video.

00:03:13.870 --> 00:03:24.040
This is a single LAN, 192.168.1.0/24, with
one router, R1, two switches, SW1 and SW2,

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:28.099
and four PCs, PC1, 2, 3, and 4.

00:03:28.099 --> 00:03:32.799
In a real network with two switches there
would be many more end hosts, but just for

00:03:32.799 --> 00:03:36.860
this demonstration I’ve attached just these
four PCs.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:42.129
SW1 is the device we’re going to focus on
today, configuring its network interfaces,

00:03:42.129 --> 00:03:49.510
including F0/1, F0/2, F0/3, and F0/4 which
are connected, as well as the remaining interfaces

00:03:49.510 --> 00:03:51.280
which are not connected at the moment.

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:56.040
Let’s go right into the CLI of SW1.

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:59.140
First I use ‘enable’ to enter privileged
exec mode.

00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:06.849
After entering privileged exec mode, I entered
the ‘show ip interface brief’, using shortcuts.

00:04:06.849 --> 00:04:12.079
As you can see, the four interfaces which
are connected to devices, fastethernet 0/1,

00:04:12.079 --> 00:04:19.690
0/2, 0/3, and 0/4 have a status column, which
is the Layer 1 status, and a protocol column,

00:04:19.690 --> 00:04:23.590
which is the Layer 2 status, of UP and UP.

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:26.780
We usually call this up/up.

00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:31.860
Keep in mind I haven’t done any configuration
on SW1 yet except set the hostname.

00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:36.360
So already we can see a difference between
Cisco routers and switches.

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:37.360
What is that?

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:41.050
Well, I mentioned briefly in the Day 8
video,

00:04:41.050 --> 00:04:46.200
router interfaces are in an administratively
disabled state by default, meaning they have

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.090
the ‘shutdown’ command applied.

00:04:49.090 --> 00:04:51.680
Switch interfaces, however, are different.

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:56.730
They don’t have the shutdown command applied,
so if you connect them to another device they’ll

00:04:56.730 --> 00:05:00.750
usually be in the up/up state with no configuration
required.

00:05:00.750 --> 00:05:06.300
Now, the IP address is unassigned, and it
will remain that way because these are layer

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:10.620
2 switchports, they don't need an IP address.

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:16.340
The concept of multilayer switching, where
you actually DO assign IP addresses to switches,

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:18.780
will be for a future lesson.

00:05:18.780 --> 00:05:22.690
For this lesson, don’t worry about the IP
address column.

00:05:22.690 --> 00:05:28.389
Now take a look at the other interfaces, keep
in mind I’m ignoring the ‘VLAN1’ virtual

00:05:28.389 --> 00:05:31.800
interface, that will be a topic for another
video.

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:38.550
These other interfaces aren’t connected
to any other devices, so their status is down/down.

00:05:38.550 --> 00:05:44.150
Keep in mind, down and down is different than
administratively down and down.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:49.889
Here’s the show ip interface brief command
on a router, notice administratively down

00:05:49.889 --> 00:05:53.740
and down, this is because of the ‘shutdown’
command’.

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:58.569
‘DOWN/DOWN’ doesn’t mean the interfaces
are shutdown, it means they aren’t connected

00:05:58.569 --> 00:06:00.030
to another device.

00:06:00.030 --> 00:06:06.390
So, to summarize, router interfaces have the
shutdown command applied by default, so they

00:06:06.390 --> 00:06:11.610
will be in the administratively down/down
state by default.

00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:15.850
Switch interfaces do not have the shutdown
command applied by default, so they will either

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:24.449
be in the up/up state, if they are connected to another
device, or the down/down state, if not connected.

00:06:24.449 --> 00:06:27.690
Now let’s look at another useful command
to check on switch interfaces.

00:06:27.690 --> 00:06:31.460
That is ‘show interfaces status’.

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:34.830
Let’s look at each field of the output.

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:39.139
First, the port field simply lists each interface.

00:06:39.139 --> 00:06:42.590
Next, you might be wondering what this ‘name’
field is.

00:06:42.590 --> 00:06:45.120
Well, its the description of the interface.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:49.341
I’m not sure why they called it ‘name’
and not ‘description’, but we’ll configure

00:06:49.341 --> 00:06:54.380
descriptions on these interfaces and you’ll
see that it appears here.

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:56.850
Next is the status field.

00:06:56.850 --> 00:07:01.880
As you can see this is different than the
status field of show ip interface brief.

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:07.349
The four connected interfaces show a status
of ‘connected, and the unconnected interfaces

00:07:07.349 --> 00:07:10.120
show a status of ‘notconnect’.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:15.610
There are other possible statuses, we’ll
cover them as they come up in the course.

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:18.259
Next is the VLAN field.

00:07:18.259 --> 00:07:23.240
VLANs will get their own video, basically
they can be used to divide LANs into smaller

00:07:23.240 --> 00:07:24.669
LANs.

00:07:24.669 --> 00:07:28.070
As you can see, the default VLAN is 1.

00:07:28.070 --> 00:07:33.099
The only one that does not show a VLAN of
1 is F0/2, which shows trunk.

00:07:33.099 --> 00:07:38.639
I won’t explain trunks now, they’ll be
covered in the VLAN video.

00:07:38.639 --> 00:07:44.210
Just take note of the fact that the interface
connected to the other switch, SW2, is a trunk

00:07:44.210 --> 00:07:46.330
interface.

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:51.590
Next is the duplex field, which as I mentioned
before indicates whether the device is capable

00:07:51.590 --> 00:07:57.410
of both sending and receiving data at the
same time, which is known as full-duplex,

00:07:57.410 --> 00:08:01.300
or if its not, which is called half-duplex.

00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:06.600
Duplex is auto by default on Cisco switches,
meaning it will negotiate with the neighboring

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:10.970
device and use full-duplex if possible.

00:08:10.970 --> 00:08:16.770
Notice that all of the unconnected interfaces
have a duplex of auto, and the connected interfaces

00:08:16.770 --> 00:08:22.979
have a duplex of ‘a dash full’ Well, the
‘a’ stands for auto, and it means that

00:08:22.979 --> 00:08:28.830
it automatically negotiated a duplex of auto
with the neighboring device.

00:08:28.830 --> 00:08:33.080
Next is the speed field, which is also auto
by default.

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:37.810
These are fastethernet interfaces, so they
are capable of speeds up to 100 megabits per

00:08:37.810 --> 00:08:39.030
second.

00:08:39.030 --> 00:08:44.450
However, they are also capable of operating
at 10 megabits per second.

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:49.030
Auto means they are able to negotiate with
the device they are connected to and use the

00:08:49.030 --> 00:08:52.820
fastest speed both devices are capable of.

00:08:52.820 --> 00:08:58.810
This time, we see ‘a DASH 100’, meaning
a speed of 100 megabits per second was auto-negotiated

00:08:58.810 --> 00:09:00.520
with the neighboring device.

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:04.900
I’ll talk in more detail about auto negotiation
soon.

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:08.140
Okay, finally is the Type field.

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:14.630
These are all RJ45 interfaces for copper UTP
cables, but if they were small form-factor

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:19.570
pluggable, or SFP, modules, you’d see that
here instead.

00:09:19.570 --> 00:09:27.010
In this case, we see 10/100BASE-TX, the 10/100
of course referring to the speeds at which

00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:31.120
these interfaces can operate.

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:36.200
Autonegotiation works well so usually you’ll
leave it be, but lets go and manually configure

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:42.850
the speed and duplex of an interface, F0/1
which is connected to R1.

00:09:42.850 --> 00:09:48.010
As you can see, I enter interface config mode,
and then use the command speed.

00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:53.900
I use the context-sensitive help to display
the next option, and I can choose between

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:57.540
10 or 100 megabits per second, or auto.

00:09:57.540 --> 00:10:03.880
So, I set the speed to 100, since R1’s interface
is a fastethernet interface also.

00:10:03.880 --> 00:10:09.150
Then, I use the command ‘duplex’ to set
the duplex of the interface.

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:15.250
As the context-sensitive help shows, I can
choose between auto, which is the default, or full

00:10:15.250 --> 00:10:17.350
and half.

00:10:17.350 --> 00:10:21.580
Both SW1 and R1 support full duplex, so I
choose that.

00:10:21.580 --> 00:10:26.860
Finally, I configure a description on the
interface, indicating that it is connected

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:28.250
to R1.

00:10:28.250 --> 00:10:34.730
Okay, so when I use the ‘show interfaces
status’ command once again, you can see

00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:40.200
both the configured description and the configured
speed and duplex.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:46.850
Notice the duplex is full, rather than a dash
full, and the speed is 100, rather than a

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:51.700
dash 100, because they are not being autonegotiated
any more.

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:58.440
Once again, normally you will keep autonegotiation
on, but if perhaps there is some problem and

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:03.800
its not working, you should know how to manually
configure the speed and duplex of an interface.

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:08.050
Now, let me quickly do some configurations
for the other connected interfaces off-camera…

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:14.730
Okay, so I just configured descriptions on
F0/2, 0/3, and 0/4.

00:11:14.730 --> 00:11:18.850
Now, how about the unused interfaces?

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:23.260
Although the fact that switch interfaces are
enabled by default is convenient, as you can

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:28.820
just plug a device in and use it straight
away, it can be a security concern.

00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:32.330
Really, you should disable the interfaces.

00:11:32.330 --> 00:11:38.001
Fortunately, instead of having to configure
each of the 8 interfaces one by one, there

00:11:38.001 --> 00:11:41.820
is a way to configure all 8 interfaces at
once.

00:11:41.820 --> 00:11:45.830
Here’s the command that can save you a lot
of time.

00:11:45.830 --> 00:11:52.600
From global config mode, type ‘interface
range’, and then enter the range like this,

00:11:52.600 --> 00:11:56.320
f0/5 to 12.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:12:02.370
This time, instead of interface config mode,
I am brought to interface range config mode,

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:05.980
and I enter a description, and then shut down
the interfaces.

00:12:05.980 --> 00:12:12.270
All at once, I get messages saying the interfaces
have changed to administratively down.

00:12:12.270 --> 00:12:17.950
Now, before we check show interfaces status
once more, let me show you a cool thing about

00:12:17.950 --> 00:12:19.950
this command.

00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:24.160
The interfaces in the range don’t all have
to be consecutive.

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:32.810
For example, if I later want to enter fastethernet
0/5, 6, 9, 10, 11, and 12, but leave 7 and

00:12:32.810 --> 00:12:43.130
8 shutdown, I can do this: interface range
f0/5 to 6, COMMA, f0/9 to 12.

00:12:43.130 --> 00:12:48.840
Then if I issue ‘no shutdown’, you can
see only those interfaces and enabled.

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:52.210
F0/7 and 8 remain down.

00:12:52.210 --> 00:12:59.960
Okay, so I shutdown interfaces f0/5,6,9,10,11,
and 12 again, and here’s the output of show

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:02.910
interfaces status again.

00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:07.990
Now you can see the description of each interface,
and the status is disabled.

00:13:07.990 --> 00:13:13.000
Once again, this status is different than the
status shown in ‘show ip interface brief’,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:19.500
which will now be ‘administratively down’,
although really they mean the same thing.

00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:24.480
Before talking about autonegotiation, I want
to explain full and half duplex.

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:30.620
I have briefly mentioned it a few times, but
haven’t explained it in depth yet.

00:13:30.620 --> 00:13:35.940
Half duplex means that the device cannot send
and receive data at the same time.

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:40.930
If it is receiving a frame, it must wait before
sending a frame.

00:13:40.930 --> 00:13:45.130
Full duplex means that the device CAN send
and receive data at the same time.

00:13:45.130 --> 00:13:47.380
It does not have to wait.

00:13:47.380 --> 00:13:51.450
Clearly, full duplex is the preferred way
to go.

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:57.420
In modern networks that use switches, all
devices can use full duplex on their interfaces.

00:13:57.420 --> 00:14:01.080
So, you may be wondering where is half-duplex
used?

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:05.940
Well, in modern day networks, almost nowhere.

00:14:05.940 --> 00:14:11.370
But to understand half-duplex let me introduce
you to an old type of network device which

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:14.620
was around before the network switch.

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:20.410
The hub is much simpler than a switch, in
fact it is simply a repeater.

00:14:20.410 --> 00:14:25.000
Any frame it receives, it floods
like a switch does with a broadcast or unknown

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.920
unicast frame.

00:14:26.920 --> 00:14:31.860
For example, if PC1 wants to send a frame
to PC2, it will send the frame out of its

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:34.520
network interface,

00:14:34.520 --> 00:14:39.430
and after the hub receives it, it will repeat
the frame out of its other interfaces, to

00:14:39.430 --> 00:14:41.480
PC2 and PC3.

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:47.800
PC3 will recognize that the destination MAC
Address is not its own and ignore the frame,

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:50.400
and PC2 will receive it normally.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:55.470
Now, what if two PCs try to send frames at
the same time?

00:14:55.470 --> 00:15:01.280
In this case, PC1 is trying to send a frame
to PC2, and PC3 is trying to send a frame

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:03.320
to PC1.

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:07.390
They both send the frames out of their network
interfaces,

00:15:07.390 --> 00:15:10.100
and this is where a problem occurs.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:14.830
The hub won’t send one first and then send
the other after, it simply tries to flood

00:15:14.830 --> 00:15:21.250
both at the same time, and this will result
in a collision on the interface, and PC2 won’t

00:15:21.250 --> 00:15:24.060
receive either frame intact.

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:28.870
All devices connected to a hub are part of
what’s called a collision domain.

00:15:28.870 --> 00:15:32.950
The frames they send could collide with frames
any of the other devices connected to the

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:35.020
hub send.

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:40.270
To deal with collisions in a half-duplex situation
like this, Ethernet devices use a mechanism

00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:42.100
called ‘CSMA/CD’.

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:45.260
Let’s check it out.

00:15:45.260 --> 00:15:52.220
CSMA/CD stands for ‘carrier sense multiple
access with collision detection’.

00:15:52.220 --> 00:15:57.500
It describes how devices avoid collisions
in a half-duplex situation, and how they react

00:15:57.500 --> 00:15:59.660
if collisions do occur.

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:01.880
It works like this.

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:07.120
Before sending frames, devices listen to the
collision domain until they detect that other

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:08.930
devices are not sending frames.

00:16:08.930 --> 00:16:15.060
If a collision does occur, which can still
happen because of bad timing and such, the

00:16:15.060 --> 00:16:20.770
device sends a jamming signal to inform the
other devices that a collision happened.

00:16:20.770 --> 00:16:25.710
Each device then waits a random period of
time before sending frames agan.

00:16:25.710 --> 00:16:30.260
The process then repeats, with each device
listening to check if other devices are sending

00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:33.280
frames before sending their own frames.

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:38.860
Now, that process works, and it was how networks
operated for a long time.

00:16:38.860 --> 00:16:42.180
But switches are more sophisticated than hubs.

00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:48.440
Hubs are simple repeaters which operate at
layer 1, repeating whatever signals they receive.

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:53.250
Switches operate at layer 2, using layer 2
addressing, MAC addresses, to send frames

00:16:53.250 --> 00:16:55.810
to specific hosts.

00:16:55.810 --> 00:16:59.350
They also won’t try to send two frames to
the same host at once.

00:16:59.350 --> 00:17:06.560
So, this network which was one collision domain
when connected to a hub, is now 1, 2, 3 collision

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:08.440
domains.

00:17:08.440 --> 00:17:13.370
Because of the improved functionality of switches
over hubs, these devices can now operate in

00:17:13.370 --> 00:17:18.300
full duplex, meaning they don’t have to
worry about whether or not other devices are

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:23.069
sending data at the same time, they can send
data freely.

00:17:23.069 --> 00:17:28.110
Although problems like collisions still do
occur, they are rare and usually are a sign

00:17:28.110 --> 00:17:34.110
of a problem, like a misconfiguration, rather
than a regular occurrence like in a half-duplex

00:17:34.110 --> 00:17:35.410
network.

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:38.330
So let’s review half and full duplex once
more.

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:43.870
In half duplex, the device cannot send and
receive data at the same time.

00:17:43.870 --> 00:17:48.360
If it is receiving a frame, it must wait before
sending a frame.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:52.490
Devices attached to a hub must operate in
half duplex.

00:17:52.490 --> 00:17:57.790
In modern networks, you’re probably not
going to use a hub, but it’s a possibility.

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:03.080
In full duplex, the device can send and receive
data at the same time, it does not have to

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:04.620
wait.

00:18:04.620 --> 00:18:08.230
Devices attached to a switch can operate in
full duplex.

00:18:08.230 --> 00:18:14.000
Okay, now that you know what duplex is let’s
talk about speed and duplex autonegotiation

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:19.880
on interfaces, and this applies to both routers
and switches by the way.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:27.290
Interfaces that can run at different speeds,
for example 10/100 or 10/100/1000, have default

00:18:27.290 --> 00:18:31.750
settings of speed auto and duplex auto.

00:18:31.750 --> 00:18:36.020
Interfaces advertise their capabilities to
their neighbors, and they negotiate the best

00:18:36.020 --> 00:18:38.600
speed and duplex settings they are both capable
of.

00:18:38.600 --> 00:18:41.520
So, let’s look at an example.

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:46.910
Here’s a small network, a switch with three
PCs connected.

00:18:46.910 --> 00:18:52.020
Connected to G0/1 is a PC with a regular ethernet
interface.

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:59.650
Connected to G0/2 is a PC with a fastethernet
interface. and connected to G0/3 is a PC with

00:18:59.650 --> 00:19:02.490
a gigabit ethernet interface.

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:07.430
As you probably know by now, an Ethernet
interface can run at 10 megabits per second,

00:19:07.430 --> 00:19:12.990
a fastethernet interface can run at 10 or
100 megabits per second, and a gigabit ethernet

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:18.650
interface can run at 10, 100, or 1000 gigabits
per second.

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:25.420
So, G0/1 and the PC will negotiate to a speed
of 10 megabits per second, and full duplex.

00:19:25.420 --> 00:19:31.420
G0/2 and the PC will negotiate to a speed
of 100 and full duplex.

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:37.420
And g0/3 and the PC will negotiate to speed
1000 and full duplex.

00:19:37.420 --> 00:19:42.040
The PCs are all able to use the max speed
of their network interfaces, and the switch

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:45.590
adjusts the speeds of its interfaces to match.

00:19:45.590 --> 00:19:50.760
In a network like this with all PCs and switches,
there’s no reason to use half-duplex, so

00:19:50.760 --> 00:19:52.980
they all negotiate to use full-duplex.

00:19:52.980 --> 00:19:57.240
Now, let’s talk about another situation.

00:19:57.240 --> 00:20:01.170
What if autonegotiation is disabled on the
device connected to the switch?

00:20:01.170 --> 00:20:06.650
So, the switch is trying to autonegotiate,
but the other devices don't respond.

00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:09.720
Well, this is how the switch will respond.

00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:13.780
For the speed, the switch will try to sense
the speed that the other device is operating

00:20:13.780 --> 00:20:15.180
at.

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:21.060
If it fails to sense the speed, it will use
the slowest supported speed, for example 10

00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:24.840
Mbps on a 10/100/1000 interface.

00:20:24.840 --> 00:20:31.890
Now, as for duplex, if it ends up using a
speed of 10 or 100 mbps, the switch will use

00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:33.790
half duplex.

00:20:33.790 --> 00:20:39.060
If the speed is 1000 mbps or greater, it will
use full duplex.

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:41.260
So let’s see how this works.

00:20:41.260 --> 00:20:47.420
In this case, only the switch is using autonegotiation,
and the three PCs have manual, fixed speed

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:49.060
and duplex settings.

00:20:49.060 --> 00:20:54.730
We’ll also assume that the switch successfully
detects the speed that the PCs are using.

00:20:54.730 --> 00:21:01.130
The Green PC has a speed of 10 Mbps, so the
switch detects that and sets its speed to

00:21:01.130 --> 00:21:02.860
the same.

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:08.230
Because its speed is 10 Mbps, it sets its
speed to half duplex.

00:21:08.230 --> 00:21:13.130
Now, how about G0/2, connected to the Red
PC?

00:21:13.130 --> 00:21:19.110
It senses that the PC is using a speed of
1000 mbps, so it uses the same.

00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:24.300
Because the speed is 1000 Mbps, it uses full
duplex.

00:21:24.300 --> 00:21:28.900
Now how about G0/3, connected to the blue
PC?

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:34.500
It senses the speed of 100 mbps, but then
what about the duplex?

00:21:34.500 --> 00:21:40.380
The PC is using full duplex, but without autonegotiation
the switch cant sense that.

00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:46.400
So, because the speed is 100 Mbps, the switch
uses half duplex.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:51.610
This results in a duplex mismatch, which will
cause collisions to occur, resulting in poor

00:21:51.610 --> 00:21:52.980
network performance.

00:21:52.980 --> 00:21:59.610
So, really you should be using autonegotiation
on all devices in the network.

00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:03.430
Now let’s take a look at some of the errors
that can show up on interfaces that otherwise

00:22:03.430 --> 00:22:05.680
seem to be working.

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:10.180
The switch will take count of some of these
things and you can view them with the ‘show

00:22:10.180 --> 00:22:11.610
interfaces’ command.

00:22:11.610 --> 00:22:15.860
We took a quick look at this command when
we were configuring router interfaces, so

00:22:15.860 --> 00:22:19.580
these things aren’t specific for switch
interfaces.

00:22:19.580 --> 00:22:24.200
This time, let’s focus on some of these
statistics at the bottom.

00:22:24.200 --> 00:22:27.370
There are lots of different kinds of counters
shown here and you don’t have to know all

00:22:27.370 --> 00:22:31.680
of them at this point, so let’s just focus
on some.

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:37.300
First up, not errors, but you can see the
total number of packets received on the interface,

00:22:37.300 --> 00:22:40.770
and the total number of bytes in those packets.

00:22:40.770 --> 00:22:42.480
Next up is runts.

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:48.160
These are frames that are smaller than the
minimum Ethernet frame size of 64 bytes.

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:53.330
Beside the runts counter is the giants counter,
which counts received frames which are larger

00:22:53.330 --> 00:22:59.260
than the ethernet maximum frame size of 1518
bytes.

00:22:59.260 --> 00:23:04.700
Next up, CRC, which counts frames which failed
their CRC check.

00:23:04.700 --> 00:23:12.020
If you remember, the CRC is the cyclic redundancy
check done via the FCS, or frame check sequence,

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:14.320
in the trailer of an ethernet frame.

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:21.260
It’s used to detect errors, and if an error
is detected this counter goes up.

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:27.260
Next is frame, which counts frames that have
an incorrect or illegal format.

00:23:27.260 --> 00:23:32.180
Input errors is a total of various counters,
including the four I just mentioned.

00:23:32.180 --> 00:23:39.600
Finally, output errors counts frames the switch
tried to send, but failed due to an error.

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:43.309
Keep in mind, I’m showing you all of these
counters on a switch, but they are the same

00:23:43.309 --> 00:23:46.630
on a router.

00:23:46.630 --> 00:23:50.690
Before moving on to today’s quiz, let’s
review what we covered.

00:23:50.690 --> 00:23:53.200
We talked about interface speed and duplex.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:57.570
I explained the concepts of full and half
duplex.

00:23:57.570 --> 00:24:02.380
Full duplex is preferred, and in most modern
networks all devices will be able to operate

00:24:02.380 --> 00:24:07.850
in full duplex, so they can send data freely
without waiting for other devices to stop

00:24:07.850 --> 00:24:09.430
sending.

00:24:09.430 --> 00:24:14.760
We talked about speed and duplex autonegotiation,
which allows devices to find the appropriate

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.890
speed and duplex settings without manual configuration.

00:24:18.890 --> 00:24:23.990
We looked a bit at interfaces status using
the ‘show interface status’ command, such

00:24:23.990 --> 00:24:28.200
as the statuses connected, notconnect, and
disabled.

00:24:28.200 --> 00:24:31.430
We’ll look more at this throughout the course.

00:24:31.430 --> 00:24:37.030
Finally, we looked at some interface counters
and errors such as runts, which are frames

00:24:37.030 --> 00:24:42.870
that don’t meet the minimum size requirements,
and giants, which exceed the maximum frame

00:24:42.870 --> 00:24:44.370
size requirements.

00:24:44.370 --> 00:24:47.770
Okay, let’s get started on the quiz.

00:24:47.770 --> 00:24:51.920
Remember, there will also be flashcards which
you can download from the link in the description

00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:54.510
to help you remember what you learned in this
video.

00:24:54.510 --> 00:24:58.140
Let’s go to question 1.

00:24:58.140 --> 00:25:04.340
There is a duplex mismatch between SW1’s
F0/1 interface and SW2’s F0/1 interface,

00:25:04.340 --> 00:25:06.809
which are connected.

00:25:06.809 --> 00:25:08.550
Autonegotiation is disabled.

00:25:08.550 --> 00:25:10.230
What will be the result?

00:25:10.230 --> 00:25:13.200
A, improved performance.

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:15.720
B, collisions will occur.

00:25:15.720 --> 00:25:21.630
Or C, SW1 will sense SW2’s duplex setting
and adjust to match.

00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:27.120
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:25:27.120 --> 00:25:30.370
The answer is B, collisions will occur.

00:25:30.370 --> 00:25:34.690
The half duplex side is unable to send and
receive data at the same time.

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:39.490
However, the full duplex side is unaware of
this, and will send data even if the half

00:25:39.490 --> 00:25:43.090
duplex side isn’t ready to receive it, causing
collisions.

00:25:43.090 --> 00:25:45.870
So, B is correct.

00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:50.770
It definitely won’t result in improved performance,
in fact performance will probably be much

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:52.670
worse, so A is incorrect.

00:25:52.670 --> 00:25:58.481
SW1 won’t be able to sense SW2’s duplex
setting without autonegotiation enabled, so

00:25:58.481 --> 00:26:00.360
C is incorrect too.

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:03.800
Let’s go to question 2.

00:26:03.800 --> 00:26:08.830
What is used on half-duplex interfaces to
detect and avoid collisions?

00:26:08.830 --> 00:26:15.070
A, CSMA/CD, B, CSMA/CA.

00:26:15.070 --> 00:26:21.150
C, Autonegotiation, or D, Duplex Auto.

00:26:21.150 --> 00:26:27.540
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:26:27.540 --> 00:26:30.710
The answer is a, CSMA/CD.

00:26:30.710 --> 00:26:37.610
CSMA CD stands for carrier sense multiple
access with collision detection.

00:26:37.610 --> 00:26:43.130
It describes how devices using half-duplex
listen for activity on a network segment,

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:47.370
and then send data only when other devices
aren't sending.

00:26:47.370 --> 00:26:51.600
It also describes how a device will react
when a collision does occur.

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:54.400
So A, CSMA/CD is correct.

00:26:54.400 --> 00:27:01.809
B, CSMA/CA, is a similar concept that we’ll
cover later in the course that stands for

00:27:01.809 --> 00:27:05.360
carrier sense multiple access with collision
avoidance.

00:27:05.360 --> 00:27:12.930
C, autonegotiation, and D, duplex auto, are
unrelated to how a half-duplex interface detects

00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:14.559
and avoids collisions.

00:27:14.559 --> 00:27:18.700
Let’s go to question 3.

00:27:18.700 --> 00:27:23.510
Which command shows various counters of errors
detected on an interface?

00:27:23.510 --> 00:27:25.670
A, show interfaces.

00:27:25.670 --> 00:27:29.440
B, show ip interface brief.

00:27:29.440 --> 00:27:32.990
C, show interfaces status.

00:27:32.990 --> 00:27:36.050
Or D, show interfaces errors.

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:42.150
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:27:42.150 --> 00:27:44.640
The answer is A, show interfaces.

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:48.870
Let’s check the output of each command.

00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:54.430
As you can see, show ip interface brief doesn’t
display any counters of errors detected on the

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:55.430
interface.

00:27:55.430 --> 00:28:00.740
It’s a useful command for checking the IP
addresses of interfaces, checking if they’re

00:28:00.740 --> 00:28:02.800
shutdown, etc.

00:28:02.800 --> 00:28:06.990
Show interfaces status also doesn’t show
any error counters.

00:28:06.990 --> 00:28:14.170
It gives some basic information about interfaces
such as description, status, duplex and speed.

00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:18.840
show interfaces errors isn’t a real command,
so an error message appears when I try to

00:28:18.840 --> 00:28:21.170
enter it.

00:28:21.170 --> 00:28:25.740
Show interfaces displays counters of errors
detected on the interface.

00:28:25.740 --> 00:28:29.920
In this case I used ‘show interface f0/1.

00:28:29.920 --> 00:28:35.190
Because so much information is given for each
interface, you probably won’t use this command

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:41.230
to view all interfaces at once, but rather
specify an individual interface to check.

00:28:41.230 --> 00:28:44.190
The counters are at the bottom of the output.

00:28:44.190 --> 00:28:47.250
So A, show interfaces, is correct.

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:51.450
Let’s go to question 4.

00:28:51.450 --> 00:28:55.520
Which are examples of errors that might occur
on a network interface?

00:28:55.520 --> 00:28:59.560
A, runts, giants, broadcasts.

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:03.590
B, shorts, longs, oversizes.

00:29:03.590 --> 00:29:08.630
C, packets, bytes, inputs, outputs.

00:29:08.630 --> 00:29:12.670
D, runts, giants, CRC.

00:29:12.670 --> 00:29:19.080
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:29:19.080 --> 00:29:23.730
The answer is D, runts, giants, CRC.

00:29:23.730 --> 00:29:29.390
The names in B and C are not real errors that
can occur on an interface.

00:29:29.390 --> 00:29:35.540
In option A, runts and giants are possible
errors, but broadcasts are not errors, they

00:29:35.540 --> 00:29:38.679
are part of normal network operations.

00:29:38.679 --> 00:29:43.830
So D, runts, giants, CRC, is the correct answer.

00:29:43.830 --> 00:29:52.080
Remember, Runts are frames that are too small,
Giants are frames that are too big, and CRC

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:57.620
counts the frames that failed their CRC check,
which is done in the frame check sequence

00:29:57.620 --> 00:29:59.740
in the trailer of the ethernet frame.

00:29:59.740 --> 00:30:03.070
Let’s go to question 5.

00:30:03.070 --> 00:30:09.800
SW1 is trying to autonegotiate interface speed
settings with SW2.

00:30:09.800 --> 00:30:13.100
However, autonegotiation is disabled on SW2’s
interface.

00:30:13.100 --> 00:30:21.010
SW2’s interface is configured with a speed
of 100 Mbps and full duplex.

00:30:21.010 --> 00:30:24.800
What speed and duplex settings will SW1 use?

00:30:24.800 --> 00:30:30.090
A, speed 100 megabits per second, duplex full.

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:35.150
B, speed 100 megabits per second, duplex half.

00:30:35.150 --> 00:30:40.100
C, speed 10 megabits per second, duplex full.

00:30:40.100 --> 00:30:44.880
Or D, Speed 10 megabits per second, duplex
half.

00:30:44.880 --> 00:30:50.740
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:30:50.740 --> 00:30:56.050
The answer is B, speed 100 megabits per second,
duplex half.

00:30:56.050 --> 00:31:01.610
If the remote device has autonegotiation disabled,
but it's enabled on the local device, the local

00:31:01.610 --> 00:31:07.340
device will attempt to sense the speed the
remote device is using, so SW1 will be able

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:12.800
to correctly set its interface speed to 100
megabits per second to match SW2’s.

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:19.461
However, it can't sense the duplex mode of
SW2’s interface, so the rule is if the speed

00:31:19.461 --> 00:31:26.140
is 10 or 100 megabits per second, half duplex
will be used, otherwise full duplex will be

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:27.380
used.

00:31:27.380 --> 00:31:32.679
In this case, half duplex will be used, which
will result in a duplex mismatch between the

00:31:32.679 --> 00:31:38.700
two devices, and probably poor performance
on the link between them due to collisions.

00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:41.940
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:31:41.940 --> 00:31:47.410
Remember to make use of the supplemental materials
for this video, I’ve made a set of flash

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:52.290
cards to be used with the flashcard software
Anki to help you remember what you learned

00:31:52.290 --> 00:31:54.770
in the video.

00:31:54.770 --> 00:31:58.890
Also, there will also be a packet tracer practice
lab to give you hands-on practice configuring

00:31:58.890 --> 00:32:00.560
Cisco devices.

00:32:00.560 --> 00:32:01.990
That will be the next video.

00:32:01.990 --> 00:32:06.450
Good luck with your studies.

